==Dependent relationships==
{{TRS-byline|Fabartus}}
Trainz dependencies are not like my sons living at little cost whilst mom and I pay for most everything, but describe a relationship of assets to parts of an asset. In the acquisition of content you will likely all too quickly come face to face with a route or session asset where a part called for in the {{TBS|kuid-table}} is no where to be found. This is in part because various people have taken up the hobby, and not all of them are inclined to donate their creations made possible only through a long process of sometimes hard research and painstaking effort...

{{TRS-underconstruction}}

{{AM&C-bot|FUN=1}}

{{ORP-top}}{{TOCright}}
[[File:CWCY 1811.JPG|left|thumb|Caldwell County Railroad #1811, EMD GP-16, photographed July 20, 2004.]]
'''KIND Engine''' assets are classified as rolling stock which contain diesel or electric loco engine performance characteristics. The related sister-KIND or class asset is TR|K|KIND Steam-engine}} which uses many if not all of the same (sub-)containers or Child classes listed below, but has a different pallet of base data which needs be modeled and defined in the parent class (i.e. the container ''''KIND Engine''''&mdash;those tags and special KIND containers discussed here below). This modular breakout should make working with {{TA|config}}s easier for the new and old Trainzers to get a handle on.
&nbsp;

==Historical engine-specs==
Formats of engine specifications evolved from the earliest Trainz versions, perhaps more than any other digital modeling group of assets, which is readily understandable given the dependency of a locomotive's driving behavior (the physical reality modeled and simulated in a digital virtual world) depend more than any other class of object on tight interaction between scripting, animation elements, and the physics model within Trainz. Unfortunately, the older Content Creator's Guides (early era, HTML pages and files, after UTC as *.pdf files) were also generally kept online for ease of updating, and cannot now*<ref
 group="notes" name="*1"> unless N3V relents, and restores the url links&mdash;a Ticket was put in about this in mid-August 2014</ref> be readily accessed  by new comers or others interested in comparing different digital models.{{TrainzTip|1=If these are of interest&mdash;especially if you have ambitions to become a Loco CC maker and want to study the old vs. the new, make pals with someone who has the older versions downloaded and will share. Better yet, lurk on {{wp|eBay}} and such other consumer to consumer retail sites and acquire the older Trainz versions.}}

The containers and gross changes in engine-specs may be compared to the current grouping of tags and containers by seeing the CCGTC Online page: {{MainCCG|CCG/Kind:_Engine|Kind: Engine}}.

